    "narrative": "The Austin Waves enter today\u2019s slate with **Jackson Merrill** serving as the undisputed anchor of the lineup. With a 75.27 efficiency score, **Jackson Merrill** benefits from a massive confluence of positive indicators: he hits in the #3 spot against Feltner, whose 4.63 xERA is the most exploitable on the docket. Further bolstering his profile is a +14% park factor boost and a +13% dynamic platoon edge, making him a must-start for both points and the high-upside speed potential against a slow-delivering opposing battery. While **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.** remains a strong play at 56.38, he faces a significantly tougher hurdle in the 2.57 xERA of Ritchie. Similarly, **Kyle Tucker** (52.03) and **Drake Baldwin** (60.73) provide reliable offensive foundations, though **Kyle Tucker** is forced to navigate the high-skill environment of a matchup against Webb, limiting his ceiling despite his elite xwOBA metrics.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was undoubtedly **Josh Jung**, who landed just below our 40-point threshold at 39.89. While **Josh Jung** possesses the raw talent to exceed that projection, the model flagged him as a risk due to the 3.09 xERA of Bubba Chandler and a lack of specific lineup momentum. We are intentionally playing conservative with our game caps to ensure we maintain roster flexibility for higher-leverage matchups later in the week. Meanwhile, **Marcell Ozuna** remains in the utility slot despite the looming threat of an elite arm in deGrom, whose presence suppresses **Marcell Ozuna**'s scoring potential despite his projected #4 order spot. We are monitoring the official lineup card for that game closely, as any drop in order positioning would likely necessitate a pinch-hit strategy to protect our efficiency metrics. \n\nWe must also contend with significant headwinds in the outfield, as **Luis Robert Jr.** (42.06) and **Andy Pages** (43.23) are both pressing against their floors due to negative park factors and the suppression effect of facing skilled pitchers like Ryan and Webb. Though we are overweighting these players for their SB potential, we remain wary of the strikeout risk inherent in those specific matchups. With **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.**, **Gunnar Henderson**, and **Jordan Westburg** currently sidelined or on an off-day, our depth is being tested; we continue to rely on the versatility of **Nasim Nunez** to bridge the gap, despite the heavy penalty imposed by his matchup against Ritchie.",
